7/ Where does the carousel stop?
6/ We’ll see Series B companies bridging to a Series C,  Series C bridging to a Series D, and so on.
5/ It's obvious this effect is going to ripple through to later financing rounds.
4/ In each case, the goal of the bridge round is to enable them to get to a Series B, where the hurdle is now $5-10M+ annualized revenues.
3/ In the past couple weeks, I’ve spoken to three companies who are raising a bridge round a year or two after raising a $5M+ Series A.
2/ Back in the good ol’ days (2013), a bridge round was intended to give post-seed companies more runway to get to a Series A.
1/ One unintended but interesting consequence of the higher bar for later rounds is the changing nature of bridge rounds.
